5.1 Parameter Drift Bound (Week 10-11)
Goal: Derive a bound on how far parameters can drift from the true gradient trajectory during momentum extrapolation phases.
Approach:
Let θ_t be the parameters at step t. During normal backprop: θ_{t+1} = θ_t - η∇L(θ_t). During momentum extrapolation: θ_{t+1} = θ_t - ηm_t, where m_t is the momentum buffer.
Define drift: D_t = ||θ_t^{LERNA} - θ_t^{full}|| (distance between LERNA's parameters and full backprop parameters).
Derive bound: Show that after K consecutive skip steps with L-smoothness assumption:
D_{t+K} ≤ ηK||m_t - ∇L(θ_t)|| + (Lη²K²/2)||m_t||
The first term is bounded by the momentum-gradient discrepancy (which is small during plateaus where gradients are small). The second term is the accumulated second-order error.
Add Proposition 1 (Plateau-conditional tightening): When skips trigger only during phases where ||∇L(θ_t)|| ≤ ε_plateau, drift tightens to O(ηK·ε_plateau). This is YOUR unique theoretical contribution.
Connect to safety horizon: Show that the adaptive safety horizon H(ρ_VG) ensures D_{t+H} < ε for a chosen tolerance ε. When ρ_VG is high (parameters aligned with gradients), H can be larger. When ρ_VG is low, H must be smaller.
5.2 Convergence Rate Analysis (Week 11-12)
Goal: Show that LERNA's hybrid switching scheme converges to a neighborhood of the optimum, and characterize the convergence rate relative to full backpropagation.
Approach:
Assume L-smooth and Polyak-Łojasiewicz (PL) condition (standard assumptions, more realistic for neural networks than strong convexity).
For full backprop under PL: E[L(θ_T) - L*] ≤ (1-μ/η)^T (L(θ_0) - L*) (linear convergence).
For LERNA with skip fraction p (fraction of steps using momentum extrapolation):
During backprop steps: standard convergence
During skip steps: bounded drift (from 5.1)
Derive corrected rate:
E[L(θ_T) - L*] ≤ (1-μη)^T (L(θ_0) - L*) + O(η²K_max²L²)
The error floor must depend on K_max (safety horizon), not just skip fraction p. This is critical because p=0.33 with K=1 is vastly different from p=0.33 with K=100.
Add the cos(φ) correction: effective progress rate is η(1-p + p·cos(φ)) where φ is angle between momentum and true gradient, not just η(1-p). When cos(φ) ≈ 1 (momentum aligned with gradient), progress is nearly full. When cos(φ) ≈ 0 (momentum orthogonal), skip steps contribute almost nothing.
Key result: When p ≈ 0.37 (matching the 37% waste finding) and ε is small (plateaus), the convergence rate is approximately 63% of full backprop but reaches a neighborhood of the same optimum. The energy savings (35-40%) exceed the convergence slowdown because skip steps cost ~0% of a full step.
5.3 Failure Mode Characterization (Week 12-13)
Goal: Theoretically and empirically characterize when LERNA fails.
Theoretical failure conditions:
False plateau detection: LER drops below threshold due to noise, not actual plateau. Momentum extrapolation during active learning causes drift.
Saddle point traps: Momentum extrapolation at saddle points pushes parameters along the momentum direction, which may not be the escape direction.
Sharp loss landscape: If the loss landscape has high curvature (large Hessian eigenvalues), small drift from extrapolation can cause large loss increases.
Momentum amplifies drift in nonstationary environments: momentum's "inertia-induced penalty" can become unbounded as β approaches 1 (cite Sahu et al. 2026).
Out-of-distribution batches during skip phases: if skip steps land on a different data distribution, momentum is entirely uncorrelated with the true loss.
Empirical failure analysis:
Run LERNA on all tasks and identify cases where accuracy degrades by >0.3%
Characterize these cases: What task properties predict failure? (dataset size, loss landscape curvature, task difficulty)
